In article <straitsCnxAEG.Mn9@netcom.com> straits@netcom.com (Stewart C. Strait) writes:
>2.  As I said about a year ago, the names sci.crypt.theory and .research
>can be interpreted as excluding discussion of mathematical and historical
>background that is no longer of 'theoretical' or 'research' interest.
>IMO, excluding 'intermediate' questions on systems that were
>laborious or impossible to break prior to computers would restrict
>the newsgroup to a tiny volume of current research plus a somewhat
>bigger volume of discussion on public key ciphers and contemporary
>block ciphers (DES, IDEA, etc.).  A disadvantage of this restriction
>is that no cryptanalytic algorithms could even be outlined, since
>all systems whose solution can be outlined in a reasonable sized post
>would be off-topic. Of course, I'm biased since I especially want
>to read 'intermediate' level discussion.

How about,
sci.crypt.technical

Mark
